Me either.

00:00:11.769 --> 00:00:12.769
Lies.

00:00:12.769 --> 00:00:15.389
Hey there liars, Trace here for DNews.

00:00:15.389 --> 00:00:20.130
My mom always warned me about lying by telling
fables and stories and anecdotes… but as

00:00:20.130 --> 00:00:24.800
I get older I began to learn that little lies
can be good too.

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:25.800
So what's the truth?

00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:27.170
Is lying bad or good?

00:00:27.170 --> 00:00:31.230
A new study in the Proceedings of the Royal
Society B[a] looked at the effects of deception

00:00:31.230 --> 00:00:35.480
in social networks, and according to their
research, white lies, specifically, smooth

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:39.910
the flow of interactions and facilitate a
larger, more integrated social group!

00:00:39.910 --> 00:00:41.840
Basically, they're saying white lies are GOOD!

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:47.800
A study published in the Journal of Basic
and Applied Psychology found we lie 2.92 times

00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:48.870
every 10 minutes!

00:00:48.870 --> 00:00:50.070
That's a lot of fibbing.

00:00:50.070 --> 00:00:54.210
Kids learn to deceive by 2 or 3 years old
and start to manipulate their parents.

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:58.640
4 years olds lie once every two hours, and
by six it's every 90 minutes!

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:00.080
We lie all the time!

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:06.170
A white lie, is a harmless or trivial falsification,
usually told to avoid hurting someone's feelings

00:01:06.170 --> 00:01:10.720
-- the researchers call this a prosocial lie;
and they're the good kind.

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:15.110
Lies told that are destructive or deceptive,
those are antisocial lies -- and they do the

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:20.340
exact opposite - weakening the bonds between
individuals and breaking down the social structure.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:25.840
They write in their paper, "The balance between
prosocial and antisocial lies may set constraints

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:30.740
on the structure of social networks, and hence
the shape of society as a whole."

00:01:30.740 --> 00:01:32.990
Lies can make or break us y'all.

00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:37.590
Using mathematical models, the researchers
revealed what most of us already know: when

00:01:37.590 --> 00:01:41.680
an individual participates in antisocial lying
they slowly isolate themselves from their

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:46.799
social group -- while pro-social liers form
stronger bonds and become more integrated.

00:01:46.799 --> 00:01:49.430
This also extends to online social networks
as well.

00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:52.321
A study at California State University, Dominguez
Hills // Huh.

00:01:52.321 --> 00:01:53.321
